Forming the southern edge of Tokyo Bay, the Miura Peninsula received its first domestic underwater cables in the 1970s. In the 1990s, international systems joined Miura to the rest of Asia, Europe, and the U.S., echoing a long history of maritime connections. In 1600, English navigator William Adams arrived in Japan and became a government advisor on shipbuilding and foreign affairs. Renamed “the pilot of Miura,” Adams settled near present-day Yokosuka in eastern Miura, now a major Japanese and U.S. naval base. More than four hundred years later, Minoru Saito became the oldest person to sail non-stop around the world at age 71, beginning and ending in Miura. The 234-day solo journey was his seventh circumnavigation.

When it opened in 1991, the North Pacific Cable was the highest-capacity system to link Japan and North America. “This pioneering effort helps usher in what futurists . . . call the fibersphere,” declared the president of Pacific Telecom, the cable’s U.S. sponsor. The following year, Tokyo Broadcasting System sent high-definition television signals between Miura and Pacific City to demonstrate the “Advantages of terrestrial fiber transmission” over satellite, including “high bandwidth, high reliability and less delay.”

Before it was cleared for industrial development in the 1970s, Tuas was a small but active fishing village on the western tip of Singapore. Local fishermen would lay palm fronds on the water’s surface above a submerged net, attracting fish with the shade. The name “Tuas” derives from the Malay word for hauling up the net and the catch it contains. Although this technique is rarely practiced anymore, modern-day Tuas pulls together large-scale networks of various kinds. Global cable systems arrived starting in the late 1990s, connecting to the red and white SingTel station, adorned with a series of porthole-shaped windows and a tall, latticework communications tower. A power plant feeds Singapore’s grid with roughly a fifth of its total supply. Near-constant marine traffic flows through the naval base, shipyards, and container port, while waste is transferred to an offshore landfill. And roadways converge at a checkpoint and mile-long bridge that links Tuas to Johor, Malaysia, offering one of the only terrestrial paths off the island.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: While early telegraph cables to Australia landed far outside Nouméa, the 2008 link to Sydney was brought into the industrial heart of New Caledonia’s capital and largest city. Owned by the Postal and Telecommunications Office, the station sits on a small, south-facing cove adjacent to a notoriously overcrowded prison and the French colony’s main container port, opened in 2006. Across the bay is a massive smelting plant that processes nearly a quarter of the global nickel supply. As container vessels depart with metal bound for Australia, Japan, and Europe, cruise ships arrive carrying tourists into the city. At the University of New Caledonia, located a short walk from the cable station, degrees are granted in French literature, network administration, and extractive metallurgy, among other subjects.

The landing site at Ban Pak Bara in Satun province is Thailand’s only cable hub on the west coast and thus handles much of the country’s signal traffic to Europe and the Middle East. Some cables also continue from Satun overland to Songkhla, linking submarine networks in the Andaman Sea and Gulf of Thailand. Although a key international node, the station is overshadowed by its natural surroundings. From your landing place on the white sand beaches of this small fishing and agricultural community, you can see modest cinderblock communications buildings and towers across the road, surrounded by acres of mangrove trees. And looking back from where you came, your view is dominated by the lush and mountainous islands of Mu Ko Phetra National Park rising out of the water.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Kitakyushu has been a networked industrial center in southern Japan for more than a century. Beginning in the early 1900s, Japan’s largest steel mill refined iron ore from Korea and China into metal for shipbuilding and the rapidly expanding railroad system. This made Kitakyushu a target during the Second World War, including the original target for the bomb later dropped on Nagasaki. Today, the city is home to Kyushu’s largest ferry port and second-largest train station, as well as a factory that produces more than three thousand miles of submarine cable each year. It’s also the birthplace of celebrated Japanese crime novelist Seichō Matsumoto. In his 1957 bestseller Points and Lines, police investigators discover two bodies on a secluded beach and use railway schedules to locate the suspects in time and space.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Carried by a secure, underwater cable from Guam, you land on Glass Beach, named for the abundant sea glass that can be found along the shore. Around you are the spherical radar stations and rocket launch facilities of the Ronald Regan Ballistic Missile Defense Test Site, which served as the command center for more than sixty U.S. nuclear tests in the Pacific after World War II. Kwajalein was a German colony in the late 1800s, then a Japanese trading post and naval stronghold in the early twentieth century until the U.S. took control in 1944. Despite being a vital node in U.S. defense networks, the island is physically small: just over one square mile and nine feet above sea level. Most residents travel by bicycle. And although the 2010 cable vastly increased communication speeds over existing satellite systems, it is also causing the base to shrink. The fiber-optic line allows more of the island’s military facilities to be operated remotely, thus reducing the need for on-site personnel.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: The Piti cable station, built just down the road from Naval Base Guam, is a fiber-optic superstation. Financed during the cable boom and was built in 2002 to land the Tyco Transpacific Network, the building is enormous, though when you enter, the reception desk remains empty, occupied only by a small security camera. You move through a large, hollow room containing rows of empty cubicles, into expansive halls of equipment, and down a cavernous hallway. On one side of the hallway is a giant battery plant in which everything is red; this is the red plant. Round plate batteries are stacked in many rows. On the other side of the hallway is a mirror version of the same plant, but blue; this is the blue plant. The station stands in contrast to the clustered, layered, and remade spaces of the Cold War buildings, Tumon and Tanguisson, further north on the island. There are no photos on the wall, or anything to mark that you are on Guam. The station has been meticulously designed, completely redundant, and with more than enough power and space to land several other systems. The station, like many others, has been overbuilt in anticipation of future growth; afterward, the market crashed and no networks landed here until 2009. There is plenty of extra room to offer to other cable networks, data or call centers, and services for digital content generation.

About four hours by plane from Tokyo, Manila, and Seoul, five hours from Taipei and Hong Kong, and seven hours from Honolulu (with direct flights from all of these cities), Guam is a point of interconnection between East Asian and American transportation routes. I arrive on the flight from Hawai‘i at A.B. Won Pat International Airport on a hot summer afternoon, where I am met by a distant relative, the son of my mother’s brother’s wife’s cousin (everyone seems to have a distant connection to Guam). While guiding me on a tour of Tumon Bay, a waterfront lined with towering, extravagant hotels, upscale designer stores, and seedy strip clubs, he asks me what brings me to the island since “it’s not on the way anywhere.” 

As I describe the cable networks that position Guam as a center for Pacific Internet traffic, I think about how this island – home to approximately 180,000 residents – is actually on the way to a number of places. It is a temporary destination for Japanese and Korean tourists, Micronesian islanders looking for an education or a job, Americans stopping for a tour on one of the two military bases, and travelers on a layover between cities. Guam is a meeting point, a site of exchange at which different kinds of flows do not simply terminate, but are interconnected.

The Kuala Muda station in Penang, commissioned in the early 1980s by Telekom Malaysia (TM), was the country’s first landing site for underwater telephone cables. As the westernmost point on the Malay Peninsula, the state of Penang made a logical terminus for the Indian Ocean Commonwealth (IOCOM) cable from Chennai, completed in 1981. While Penang’s nineteenth-century telegraph connections surfaced in the bustling heart of colonial George Town, IOCOM and subsequent cables landed ten miles north in a comparably remote area where the Muda River flows into the Malacca Strait. By placing the station on the outskirts, TM minimized the risk of cable damage from anchors and trawls of passing ships. Today, the company controls all four of Malaysia’s cable hubs (and five smaller stations), similarly positioned in fishing villages and beach towns on the urban fringe.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: As a landing site for the 1983 ASEAN cable, Songkhla was the first station in Thailand to receive underwater telephone links. Cables surface on the idyllic Ban Kao Seng beach near the country’s largest natural lake, the same place where invading Japanese troops landed at the start of the Second World War. Years earlier, according to local folklore, a wealthy governor from the south of Thailand was sailing up the coast with a fortune in gold when his ship ran aground near Ban Kao Seng. Stranded, the governor ordered his fortune buried, committed suicide, and left instructions for his severed head to be placed on the rocky cliffs above the beach. The name Kao Seng derives from the treasure’s supposed value: 900,000 baht. Some believe it’s still buried there alongside several underwater cables entering the Gulf of Thailand.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: The ASEAN (Association of South East Asian Nations) submarine cable was inaugurated in 1983 by “a three-way conversation among the Communications Ministers of Malaysia, Singapore, and Thailand,” reports the New Straits Times. With landing stations in all three countries, the cable had a capacity of 1,680 telephone lines and carried telegraph and telex messages as well. But the inauguration placed the most emphasis on the cable system’s political significance. It represented “the unity, understanding, and cooperation among the five ASEAN nations” and “exemplified their strong dedication to work towards common objectives beneficial to all.”

http://purl.org/dc/terms/bibliographicCi.value: Source: “Three-way Link-up launched,” New Straits Times, 28 September 1983: 2.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: A seventy-foot whale skeleton occupies a public plaza in central Wada. This small town outside Tokyo is also home to a dedicated landing station for the FLAG North Asian Loop cable, a kind of underwater skeletal system for communication in Asia. While the station is relatively new, whaling has been central to the culture and economy since the early 1600s. Today, Wada is one of only two places in Japan where it’s still permitted, and efforts are made to keep the tradition alive despite international bans. Every June, local schoolchildren gather to watch the first whale being brought ashore and butchered, followed by a community meal of fried whale, rice, and watermelon. Optical cables land far more discretely but in growing numbers along this stretch of the outer Bōsō Peninsula, now crowded with cable stations. Although across the Pacific, cable companies have to worry about people digging up their land lines, the coastal area of Wada is safe. Because of the local culture, one cableman says, people stick by their agreements to stay off the route that the telecommunications company bought. As a result, they have only needed to install a single line between the cable station and the landing point, compared to redundant lines that must be extended everywhere else.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: According to local legend, Pohnpei was created when ancient sailors piled rocks in the middle of the ocean. To protect the new island from waves, they surrounded it with a ring of coral reef. You cross this threshold on your approach to Kolonia, Pohnpei’s main port and largest town. This is a place of sharp contrasts. With no natural sand beaches to ease your transition, you surface abruptly near the city center where the Federated States of Micronesia Telecommunications Company cable station is located. The modern, two-story building and large satellite dish stand next to the stalls of street-vendors selling yams, bananas, breadfruit, and coconuts. On the blocks around the station, newer houses and hotels are interspersed with relics from the colonial era, including a Spanish fort from the 1880s, a turn-of-the-century German Catholic church, and several rusted, vine-covered Japanese tanks left over from World War II. Beyond that, paved roads quickly give way to mountainous jungle.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Appropriately named Keoje, Korean for “great crossing,” this island is the landing site of several international submarine cable networks, though it is still smaller than the hub in nearby Pusan. As you come ashore through clear waters, the sound you hear is not heavy rainfall but the pebbles on Hakdong beach tumbling in the surf. Named after a crane (“hak” in Korean), this wing-shaped beach sits in a valley covered by flowering camellia plants, sheltered from the industrial shipyards and granite mines further north. Eschewing the discrete architecture of many contemporary cable facilities, the Korea Telecom landing station calls attention to itself with an ornate design. Decorative columns and topiaries line the station’s brick and glass entryway, which faces away from Hakdong’s beachfront promenade.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Overcoming powerful waves and currents, you reach the coral rubble shores of Majuro. Signals travel to this ring-shaped atoll through a commercial extension of a U.S. military cable, completed in 2010, that links Guam’s network hub to a missile defense facility on Kwajalein. Though geographically isolated, Majuro is the capital city and commercial center of the Marshall Islands, home to nearly half the country’s population. From the beach, you move underneath crowded streets to the cable station, owned by the National Telecommunications Authority, next to a sports field and two large satellite dishes. Go a few blocks further, and you reach the Majuro lagoon, which holds a busy regional port. Ships arrive delivering supplies to the resource-starved island and depart carrying exports including aquarium fish and black pearls. More recently, the low-lying city has emerged as a node in the struggle to mitigate rising sea levels. In 2013, leaders of sixteen Pacific nations gathered to sign the Majuro Declaration to take action on global climate change.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: The remote village of Ishikari flourished in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries as a center of salmon fishing. One of its oldest standing structures is a 1694 shrine dedicated to the fish deity Same-sama. But as catches steadily declined in the 1900s, Ishikari expanded to become a shipping and communications gateway for the larger neighboring city of Sapporo. The first ship to arrive in the new harbor in 1982 was the Blanca Rainier from Sakhalin carrying 3,500 tons of raw timber. A ceremony held the next day marked the port’s entry into international freight circuits. Twenty-six years later, a fiber optic cable was laid along the same path, joining Russian and Japanese networks. Today, Ishikari is by far Japan’s northernmost cable station and the only landing site on the island of Hokkaido.

This 300-mile cable connects northern Japan to Russia’s terrestrial cable system, providing a shorter path between Japan and Europe compared to southern oceanic routes. It was completed in 2008 and is jointly owned by Japan’s NTT Corporation and TransTelekom of Russia.
